{"title_page": "John C. Whitehead", "text_new": "{{Infobox US Cabinet official\n|birth_name=John Cunningham Whitehead\n| image             = John_C_Whitehead.png\n| imagesize         = 150px\n| caption           =\n| order             = 9th\n| office            = U.S. Deputy Secretary of State\n| term_start        = July 9, 1985\n| term_end          = January 20, 1989\n| president         = [[Ronald Reagan]]\n| predecessor       = [[Kenneth W. Dam]]\n| successor         = [[Lawrence S. Eagleburger]]\n| birth_date        = {{Birth date|1922|4|2|}}\n| birth_place       = [[Evanston, Illinois|Evanston]], [[Illinois]], U.S.\n| death_date        = {{Death date and age|2015|2|7|1922|4|2}}\n| death_place       = [[New York City|New York]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| nationality       = United States\n| party             = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]\n| spouse            = Cynthia Matthews<br />[[Nancy Dickerson]] (1989-1997; her death)\n| children          = 3\n| alma_mater        = [[Haverford College]] <br /> [[Harvard Business School]]\n| occupation        = [[Investment banking|Investment banker]] <br /> [[Political appointee]]\n| religion          = [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopalian]]}}\n\n:''For other people named John Whitehead, see [[John Whitehead (disambiguation)]].''\n\n'''John Cunningham Whitehead''' (April 2, 1922 \u2013 February 7, 2015) was an [[Americans|American]] [[banker]] and [[civil servant]], a board member of the [[World Trade Center Memorial#World Trade Center Memorial Foundation, Inc.|World Trade Center Memorial Foundation]] (WTC Memorial Foundation), and, until his resignation in May 2006, chairman of the [[Lower Manhattan Development Corporation]].<ref>[http://www.lowermanhattan.info/news/whitehead_resigns_as_lmdc_17506.aspx \"John Whitehead Resigns as LMDC Chairman\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070808044502/http://www.lowermanhattan.info/news/whitehead_resigns_as_lmdc_17506.aspx |date=2007-08-08 }}, lowermanhattan.info; accessed February 14, 2015.</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nWhitehead was born in [[Evanston, Illinois]], the son of Winifred K. and Eugene Cunningham Whitehead.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books/about/A_Life_in_Leadership.html?id=Yj9gme99Fj4C&printsec=frontcover&source=kp_read_button&hl=en#v=onepage&q&f=false''A Life in Leadership''], ''books.google.com''.</ref> His family moved to [[Montclair, New Jersey]], when he was two years old.<ref name=\"John Whitehead\">[http://www.hbs.edu/entrepreneurs/pdf/johnwhitehead.pdf ''\"John Whitehead\"''] interview @ [[Harvard Business School]] by Amy Blitz, Director of Media Development for Entrepreneurial Management, July 2002.</ref>\n\nWhitehead graduated from [[Haverford College]] in 1943 and served in the [[U.S. Navy]] during [[World War II]], where he commanded one of the [[LCVP (United States)|LCDP]] landing crafts at [[Omaha Beach]], in the [[D-Day]] landing invasion of [[Normandy]].<ref name=BasicBooks>[http://www.perseusbooksgroup.com/basic/book_detail.jsp?isbn=0465050549 ''A Life In Leadership''] @ Basic Books</ref><ref>[https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB121503561463124251?mod=opinion_journal_main_stories ''\"A Day at the Beach\"''] @ OpinionJournal - July 4, 2008</ref>\n\nIn 1947, he received an [[MBA]] degree from [[Harvard Business School]]<ref name=\"John Whitehead\"/>\n\n==Career==\nWhitehead started his career at the New York [[investment bank]] of [[Goldman Sachs]] as an associate in the investment banking division. He quickly became a partner in the firm. He rose to become Chairman over a total of 38 years at the firm and retired in 1984 as Co-Chairman and Co-Senior Partner.\n\nWhitehead served as [[United States Deputy Secretary of State]] in [[Ronald Reagan]]'s [[Reagan Administration|administration]] from 1985 to 1989 under [[George Shultz]], and was awarded the [[Presidential Citizens Medal]] by President Reagan. In 1996, he was the Campaign Chairman for [[Michael Benjamin Bonheur|Michael Benjamin]] who ran for a seat in [[New York's 8th congressional district]].\n\nHe was Chairman at different times of the Board of the [[Federal Reserve Bank of New York]], the [[United Nations Association]], the [[Andrew W. Mellon Foundation]] and the [[Harvard Board of Overseers]]. He was a director of the [[New York Stock Exchange]] and Chairman Emeritus of The [[Brookings Institution]]. He was a member of [[Kappa Beta Phi]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Roose |first=Kevin |date=2014 |title=Young Money: Inside the Hidden World of Wall Street's Post-Crash Recruits |location=London, UK |publisher= John Murray (Publishers), An Hachette UK Company |page=206 |isbn=978-1-47361-161-0}}</ref>\n\nHe had a long association with the [[Rockefeller family]], having held positions at various times with family-created institutions such as [[Rockefeller University]], the [[Asia Society]] (where he was Chairman Emeritus and Honorary Life Trustee), the [[Lincoln Center]] Theater and the WTC Memorial Foundation. In these organisations, and previously when he was for a time on the family's powerful Trust Committee, overseeing the family fortune and investments of the [[Rockefeller Group]]{{Citation needed|date=November 2008}}, the real estate firm that previously owned and managed [[Rockefeller Center]], he became closely associated with [[David Rockefeller]].\n\nAs an alumnus of [[Haverford College]] in [[Pennsylvania]], he has had the campus center and the chair of the philosophy department named after him.\n\n\"In 1995, he donated $10 million to Harvard Business School to start the John C. Whitehead Fund for Not-for-Profit Management. In 1997, Seton Hall University in New Jersey, with Mr. Whitehead's financing, the [[School of Diplomacy and International Relations]] at [[Seton Hall University]] was also named after him.<ref name=\"nytimesobit\"/> He received an honorary [[LL.D.]] from [[Bates College]] in 2004, and an honorary Doctor of Humane Letters degree from [[The City University of New York]] upon the recommendation of [[Macaulay Honors College]] in 2009.\n\nWhitehead was an [[Eagle Scout (Boy Scouts of America)|Eagle Scout]] and recipient of the [[Distinguished Eagle Scout Award]]. He was longstanding Co-Chairman of the Board of the Greater New York Councils, Boy Scouts of America. The National Council of the Boy Scouts of America recognized his service with the [[Silver Buffalo Award]] in 2015. He was the Chairman of the [[Financial Services Volunteer Corps]] (FSVC) from July, 2005 into his death in February 2015. He was also an Advisory Board member for the [[Partnership for a Secure America]], a not-for-profit organization dedicated to recreating the bipartisan center in American national security and foreign policy. {{citation needed|date=February 2015}}\n\nWhitehead sat on the Advisory Board of the [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]]-based think-tank [[Global Financial Integrity]], which conducts research on [[illicit financial flows]] and the damaging effects they have on developing countries, as well as the advisory board for DC-based nonprofit [[America Abroad Media]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://americaabroadmedia.org/user/68/John_C._Whitehead |title=Archived copy |accessdate=June 16, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140716124816/http://americaabroadmedia.org/user/68/John_C._Whitehead |archivedate=July 16, 2014 }}</ref> He was also a member of the Board of Trustees of [[Eisenhower Fellowships]].\n\nWhitehead was a board member and head of the investment committee of the [[J. Paul Getty Trust|Getty Trust]]. He retired from that position in 1996 following a substantial portfolio loss from the use of stock options for a so-called \"[[Collar (finance)|collar]]\".<ref>Hiltzik, Michael A., [http://articles.latimes.com/1997/dec/04/news/mn-60488 \"Bad Guess on Market Cost Getty Trust $400 Million\"], Los Angeles ''Times'', December 4, 1997. Retrieved 2015-05-22.</ref>\n\nIn 2004, he received the David Rockefeller Bridging Leadership Award from Synergos.<ref>[http://www.synergos.org/universityforanight/04/ \"University for a Night 2004\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150209152555/http://www.synergos.org/universityforanight/04/ |date=2015-02-09 }}, ''synergos.org'', November 16, 2004.</ref>\n\nWhitehead was Co-Chairman of [https://web.archive.org/web/20190126222118/http://www.amdec.org/ AMDeC Foundation], a 28-member organization of leaders in [[Medical research|biomedical research and technology]] in New York State. Whitehead, along with Academic Medicine Development Company (AMDeC) President, Dr. Maria K. Mitchell, secured funding and infrastructure support for next-generation research for New York's renowned academic medical centers. In 2006, Whitehead was one of the most notable Republican donors to the campaign of [[Joe Lieberman]] during his independent re-election campaign for the [[United States Senate]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Lightman|first=David|title=GOP Gave Joe A Boost|publisher=Hartford Courant|date=March 19, 2007|url=http://www.courant.com/news/politics/hc-joemoney0319.artmar19,0,1424810.story?coll=hc-headlines-home|accessdate=2007-03-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070322165307/http://www.courant.com/news/politics/hc-joemoney0319.artmar19,0,1424810.story?coll=hc-headlines-home|archive-date=2007-03-22|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, John Whitehead joined hands with late actor [[Paul Newman]] and Josh Weston, former chairman of ADP, to co-found [[Safe Water Network]], to improve access to safe water to underserved communities around the world.\n\nOn November 12, 2008, Whitehead said at the Reuters Global Finance Summit that the United States economy faces an economic slump deeper than the Great Depression and that a growing deficit threatens the credit of the country.<ref name=Reuters>Giannone, Joseph A., [https://www.reuters.com/article/Finance08/idUSTRE4AB7HT20081112 \"Whitehead Sees Slump Worse Than Depression\"], Reuters, November 12, 2008.</ref>\n\nIn 2011, John C. Whitehead was awarded the Truman-Reagan Medal of Freedom.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.victimsofcommunism.org/about/trmedalrecipients.php |title=Archived copy |accessdate=September 4, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120828165800/http://victimsofcommunism.org/about/trmedalrecipients.php |archivedate=August 28, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Whitehead was awarded the Freedom Prize for the second time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2012/11/08/international-rescue-committee-honors-john-c-whitehead|work=[[Wall Street Journal]]|date=2012-11-08|accessdate=2013-09-06|title=Kissinger, Bloomberg Honor IRC at Freedom Award Dinner|first=Monika|last=Anderson}}</ref> He was also a member of the Steering Committee of the [[Bilderberg Group]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bilderbergmeetings.org/former-steering-committee-members.html |title=Former Steering Committee Members |work=bilderbergmeetings.org |publisher=[[Bilderberg Group]] |accessdate=2014-02-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202095633/http://www.bilderbergmeetings.org/former-steering-committee-members.html |archivedate=2014-02-02 }}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\nIn 2005, Whitehead published a memoir, ''A Life In Leadership: From D-Day to Ground Zero''.<ref name=BasicBooks/>\n\n===Select publications===\n* Whitehead, John C. [https://tspace.library.utoronto.ca/handle/1807/4887 \"Towards a Stronger International Economy.\"] Bissell Paper No. 7. Toronto: University of Toronto, Centre for International Studies, 1988.\n\n==Personal life==\nWhitehead married television newswoman [[Nancy Dickerson]] in 1989,<ref name=\"Severo\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/10/19/us/nancy-dickerson-70-first-woman-to-be-a-reporter-at-cbs.html|title=Nancy Dickerson, 70, First Woman to Be a Reporter at CBS|last=Severo|first=Richard|date=1997-10-19|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-04-04|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> by which marriage he gained seven stepchildren. She died in 1997.<ref name=\"Severo\"/> Her son, [[John Dickerson (journalist)|John Dickerson]], the writer, is one of his stepchildren. In 2003, Whitehead dedicated the Nancy Dickerson Whitehead Community Service Center for Homeless Youth in [[Southeast Washington, D.C.]], with a generous gift to [[Covenant House]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/local/2003/05/01/for-troubled-youths-a-new-haven/4c19f5e3-73c6-45da-ba3a-7aa6c0212faf/|title=For Troubled Youths, a New Haven|last=Wilson|first=Timothy|date=2003-05-01|work=Washington Post|access-date=2018-04-04|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> Whitehead died on February 7, 2015, of cancer at his New York home, at age 92.<ref name=\"nytimesobit\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/08/nyregion/john-c-whitehead-a-leader-in-finance-and-government-dies-at-92.html|title=John C. Whitehead, Who Led Effort to Rebuild After 9/11, Dies at 92|newspaper=New York Times|first=Douglas| last=Martin| date=February 8, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=John Whitehead, former leader of Goldman Sachs, dies at 92|url= https://www.reuters.com/article/us-goldman-whitehead-idUSKBN0LB0NU20150207| work=Reuters|first=Doina|last= Chiacu|date=February 7, 2015}}</ref> Earlier marriages to the former Helene Shannon, known as Sandy, and the former Jaan Chartener ended in divorce.<ref name=\"nytimesobit\"/>\n\nWhitehead was survived by his wife, the former Cynthia Matthews; his three children: Anne, Sarah and J. Gregory Whitehead; two granddaughters; seven stepchildren; and 18 step-grandchildren.<ref name=\"nytimesobit\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.gs.com/our_firm/our_culture/social_responsibility/gs_foundation/articles/board_of_trustees_article_030616194436.html Goldman Sachs biography], gs.com; accessed February 14, 2015.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061006025538/http://www.clarke.edu/news/NDWMedallion/whitehead.htm Biodata], clarke.edu; accessed February 14, 2015.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20190126222118/http://www.amdec.org/ AMDeC Foundation]\n*{{C-SPAN|John Whitehead}}\n*[http://id.lib.harvard.edu/ead/bak00292/catalog John C. Whitehead papers] at Baker Library Special Collections, Harvard Business School.\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box | title=[[United States Deputy Secretary of State]]| before=[[Kenneth W. Dam]]| after=[[Lawrence Eagleburger]]| years=1985\u20131989}}\n{{s-bus}}\n{{succession box| title=[[Chair (official)|Chairman]] and [[CEO]], [[Goldman Sachs]]| before=[[Gus Levy]]|| after=[[John Weinberg]]| years=1976\u20131985}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{USDeputySecretaryofState}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Whitehead, John C.}}\n[[Category:1922 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:American investment bankers]]\n[[Category:American military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from New York City]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Chairmen of Goldman Sachs]]\n[[Category:Chief Executive Officers of Goldman Sachs]]\n[[Category:Distinguished Eagle Scouts]]\n[[Category:Harvard Business School alumni]]\n[[Category:Haverford College alumni]]\n[[Category:Members of the Steering Committee of the Bilderberg Group]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Republicans]]\n[[Category:Seton Hall University]]\n[[Category:People from Essex Fells, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from Evanston, Illinois]]\n[[Category:People from Montclair, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Place of death missing]]\n[[Category:Presidential Citizens Medal recipients]]\n[[Category:United States Deputy Secretaries of State]]\n[[Category:American Episcopalians]]\n[[Category:Writers from Evanston, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Writers from New Jersey]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox US Cabinet official\n|birth_name=John Cunningham Whitehead\n| image             = John_C_Whitehead.png\n| imagesize         = 150px\n| caption           =\n| order             = 9th\n| office            = U.S. Deputy Secretary of State\n| term_start        = July 9, 1985\n| term_end          = January 20, 1989\n| president         = [[Ronald Reagan]]\n| predecessor       = [[Kenneth W. Dam]]\n| successor         = [[Lawrence S. Eagleburger]]\n| birth_date        = {{Birth date|1922|4|2|}}\n| birth_place       = [[Evanston, Illinois|Evanston]], [[Illinois]], U.S.\n| death_date        = {{Death date and age|2015|2|7|1922|4|2}}\n| death_place       = [[New York City|New York]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| nationality       = United States\n| party             = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]\n| spouse            = Cynthia Matthews<br />[[Nancy Dickerson]] (1989-1997; her death)\n| children          = 3\n| alma_mater        = [[Haverford College]] <br /> [[Harvard Business School]]\n| occupation        = [[Investment banking|Investment banker]] <br /> [[Political appointee]]\n| religion          = [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopalian]]}}\n\n:''For other people named John Whitehead, see [[John Whitehead (disambiguation)]].''\n\n'''John Cunningham Whitehead''' (April 2, 1922 \u2013 February 7, 2015) was an [[Americans|American]] [[banker]] and [[civil servant]], a board member of the [[World Trade Center Memorial#World Trade Center Memorial Foundation, Inc.|World Trade Center Memorial Foundation]] (WTC Memorial Foundation), and, until his resignation in May 2006, chairman of the [[Lower Manhattan Development Corporation]].<ref>[http://www.lowermanhattan.info/news/whitehead_resigns_as_lmdc_17506.aspx \"John Whitehead Resigns as LMDC Chairman\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070808044502/http://www.lowermanhattan.info/news/whitehead_resigns_as_lmdc_17506.aspx |date=2007-08-08 }}, lowermanhattan.info; accessed February 14, 2015.</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nWhitehead was born in [[Evanston, Illinois]], the son of Winifred K. and Eugene Cunningham Whitehead.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books/about/A_Life_in_Leadership.html?id=Yj9gme99Fj4C&printsec=frontcover&source=kp_read_button&hl=en#v=onepage&q&f=false''A Life in Leadership''], ''books.google.com''.</ref> His family moved to [[Montclair, New Jersey]], when he was two years old.<ref name=\"John Whitehead\">[http://www.hbs.edu/entrepreneurs/pdf/johnwhitehead.pdf ''\"John Whitehead\"''] interview @ [[Harvard Business School]] by Amy Blitz, Director of Media Development for Entrepreneurial Management, July 2002.</ref>\n\nWhitehead graduated from [[Haverford College]] in 1943 and served in the [[U.S. Navy]] during [[World War II]], where he commanded one of the [[LCVP (United States)|LCDP]] landing crafts at [[Omaha Beach]], in the [[D-Day]] landing invasion of [[Normandy]].<ref name=BasicBooks>[http://www.perseusbooksgroup.com/basic/book_detail.jsp?isbn=0465050549 ''A Life In Leadership''] @ Basic Books</ref><ref>[https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB121503561463124251?mod=opinion_journal_main_stories ''\"A Day at the Beach\"''] @ OpinionJournal - July 4, 2008</ref>\n\nIn 1947, he received an [[MBA]] degree from [[Harvard Business School]]<ref name=\"John Whitehead\"/>\n\n==Career==\nWhitehead started his career at the New York [[investment bank]] of [[Goldman Sachs]] as an associate in the investment banking division. He quickly became a partner in the firm. He rose to become Chairman over a total of 38 years at the firm and retired in 1984 as Co-Chairman and Co-Senior Partner.\n\nWhitehead served as [[United States Deputy Secretary of State]] in [[Ronald Reagan]]'s [[Reagan Administration|administration]] from 1985 to 1989 under [[George Shultz]], and was awarded the [[Presidential Citizens Medal]] by President Reagan. In 1996, he was the Campaign Chairman for [[Michael Benjamin Bonheur|Michael Benjamin]] who ran for a seat in [[New York's 8th congressional district]].\n\nHe was Chairman at different times of the Board of the [[Federal Reserve Bank of New York]], the [[United Nations Association]], the [[Andrew W. Mellon Foundation]] and the [[Harvard Board of Overseers]]. He was a director of the [[New York Stock Exchange]] and Chairman Emeritus of The [[Brookings Institution]]. He was a member of [[Kappa Beta Phi]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Roose |first=Kevin |date=2014 |title=Young Money: Inside the Hidden World of Wall Street's Post-Crash Recruits |location=London, UK |publisher= John Murray (Publishers), An Hachette UK Company |page=206 |isbn=978-1-47361-161-0}}</ref>\n\nHe had a long association with the [[Rockefeller family]], having held positions at various times with family-created institutions such as [[Rockefeller University]], the [[Asia Society]] (where he was Chairman Emeritus and Honorary Life Trustee), the [[Lincoln Center]] Theater and the WTC Memorial Foundation. In these organisations, and previously when he was for a time on the family's powerful Trust Committee, overseeing the family fortune and investments of the [[Rockefeller Group]]{{Citation needed|date=November 2008}}, the real estate firm that previously owned and managed [[Rockefeller Center]], he became closely associated with [[David Rockefeller]].\n\nAs an alumnus of [[Haverford College]] in [[Pennsylvania]], he has had the campus center and the chair of the philosophy department named after him.\n\n\"In 1995, he donated $10 million to Harvard Business School to start the John C. Whitehead Fund for Not-for-Profit Management. In 1997, Seton Hall University in New Jersey, with Mr. Whitehead's financing, the [[School of Diplomacy and International Relations]] at [[Seton Hall University]] was also named after him.<ref name=\"nytimesobit\"/> He received an honorary [[LL.D.]] from [[Bates College]] in 2004, and an honorary Doctor of Humane Letters degree from [[The City University of New York]] upon the recommendation of [[Macaulay Honors College]] in 2009.\n\nWhitehead was an [[Eagle Scout (Boy Scouts of America)|Eagle Scout]] and recipient of the [[Distinguished Eagle Scout Award]]. He was longstanding Co-Chairman of the Board of the Greater New York Councils, Boy Scouts of America. The National Council of the Boy Scouts of America recognized his service with the [[Silver Buffalo Award]] in 2015. He was the Chairman of the [[Financial Services Volunteer Corps]] (FSVC) from July, 2005 into his death in February 2015. He was also an Advisory Board member for the [[Partnership for a Secure America]], a not-for-profit organization dedicated to recreating the bipartisan center in American national security and foreign policy. {{citation needed|date=February 2015}}\n\nWhitehead sat on the Advisory Board of the [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]]-based think-tank [[Global Financial Integrity]], which conducts research on [[illicit financial flows]] and the damaging effects they have on developing countries, as well as the advisory board for DC-based nonprofit [[America Abroad Media]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://americaabroadmedia.org/user/68/John_C._Whitehead |title=Archived copy |accessdate=June 16, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140716124816/http://americaabroadmedia.org/user/68/John_C._Whitehead |archivedate=July 16, 2014 }}</ref> He was also a member of the Board of Trustees of [[Eisenhower Fellowships]].\n\nWhitehead was a board member and head of the investment committee of the [[J. Paul Getty Trust|Getty Trust]]. He retired from that position in 1996 following a substantial portfolio loss from the use of stock options for a so-called \"[[Collar (finance)|collar]]\".<ref>Hiltzik, Michael A., [http://articles.latimes.com/1997/dec/04/news/mn-60488 \"Bad Guess on Market Cost Getty Trust $400 Million\"], Los Angeles ''Times'', December 4, 1997. Retrieved 2015-05-22.</ref>\n\nIn 2004, he received the David Rockefeller Bridging Leadership Award from Synergos.<ref>[http://www.synergos.org/universityforanight/04/ \"University for a Night 2004\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150209152555/http://www.synergos.org/universityforanight/04/ |date=2015-02-09 }}, ''synergos.org'', November 16, 2004.</ref>\n\nWhitehead was Co-Chairman of [https://web.archive.org/web/20190126222118/http://www.amdec.org/ AMDeC Foundation], a 28-member organization of leaders in [[Medical research|biomedical research and technology]] in New York State. Whitehead, along with Academic Medicine Development Company (AMDeC) President, Dr. Maria K. Mitchell, secured funding and infrastructure support for next-generation research for New York's renowned academic medical centers. In 2006, Whitehead was one of the most notable Republican donors to the campaign of [[Joe Lieberman]] during his independent re-election campaign for the [[United States Senate]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Lightman|first=David|title=GOP Gave Joe A Boost|publisher=Hartford Courant|date=March 19, 2007|url=http://www.courant.com/news/politics/hc-joemoney0319.artmar19,0,1424810.story?coll=hc-headlines-home|accessdate=2007-03-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070322165307/http://www.courant.com/news/politics/hc-joemoney0319.artmar19,0,1424810.story?coll=hc-headlines-home|archive-date=2007-03-22|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn November 12, 2008, Whitehead said at the Reuters Global Finance Summit that the United States economy faces an economic slump deeper than the Great Depression and that a growing deficit threatens the credit of the country.<ref name=Reuters>Giannone, Joseph A., [https://www.reuters.com/article/Finance08/idUSTRE4AB7HT20081112 \"Whitehead Sees Slump Worse Than Depression\"], Reuters, November 12, 2008.</ref>\n\nIn 2011, John C. Whitehead was awarded the Truman-Reagan Medal of Freedom.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.victimsofcommunism.org/about/trmedalrecipients.php |title=Archived copy |accessdate=September 4, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120828165800/http://victimsofcommunism.org/about/trmedalrecipients.php |archivedate=August 28, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Whitehead was awarded the Freedom Prize for the second time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2012/11/08/international-rescue-committee-honors-john-c-whitehead|work=[[Wall Street Journal]]|date=2012-11-08|accessdate=2013-09-06|title=Kissinger, Bloomberg Honor IRC at Freedom Award Dinner|first=Monika|last=Anderson}}</ref> He was also a member of the Steering Committee of the [[Bilderberg Group]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bilderbergmeetings.org/former-steering-committee-members.html |title=Former Steering Committee Members |work=bilderbergmeetings.org |publisher=[[Bilderberg Group]] |accessdate=2014-02-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202095633/http://www.bilderbergmeetings.org/former-steering-committee-members.html |archivedate=2014-02-02 }}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\nIn 2005, Whitehead published a memoir, ''A Life In Leadership: From D-Day to Ground Zero''.<ref name=BasicBooks/>\n\n===Select publications===\n* Whitehead, John C. [https://tspace.library.utoronto.ca/handle/1807/4887 \"Towards a Stronger International Economy.\"] Bissell Paper No. 7. Toronto: University of Toronto, Centre for International Studies, 1988.\n\n==Personal life==\nWhitehead married television newswoman [[Nancy Dickerson]] in 1989,<ref name=\"Severo\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/10/19/us/nancy-dickerson-70-first-woman-to-be-a-reporter-at-cbs.html|title=Nancy Dickerson, 70, First Woman to Be a Reporter at CBS|last=Severo|first=Richard|date=1997-10-19|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-04-04|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> by which marriage he gained seven stepchildren. She died in 1997.<ref name=\"Severo\"/> Her son, [[John Dickerson (journalist)|John Dickerson]], the writer, is one of his stepchildren. In 2003, Whitehead dedicated the Nancy Dickerson Whitehead Community Service Center for Homeless Youth in [[Southeast Washington, D.C.]], with a generous gift to [[Covenant House]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/local/2003/05/01/for-troubled-youths-a-new-haven/4c19f5e3-73c6-45da-ba3a-7aa6c0212faf/|title=For Troubled Youths, a New Haven|last=Wilson|first=Timothy|date=2003-05-01|work=Washington Post|access-date=2018-04-04|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> Whitehead died on February 7, 2015, of cancer at his New York home, at age 92.<ref name=\"nytimesobit\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/08/nyregion/john-c-whitehead-a-leader-in-finance-and-government-dies-at-92.html|title=John C. Whitehead, Who Led Effort to Rebuild After 9/11, Dies at 92|newspaper=New York Times|first=Douglas| last=Martin| date=February 8, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=John Whitehead, former leader of Goldman Sachs, dies at 92|url= https://www.reuters.com/article/us-goldman-whitehead-idUSKBN0LB0NU20150207| work=Reuters|first=Doina|last= Chiacu|date=February 7, 2015}}</ref> Earlier marriages to the former Helene Shannon, known as Sandy, and the former Jaan Chartener ended in divorce.<ref name=\"nytimesobit\"/>\n\nWhitehead was survived by his wife, the former Cynthia Matthews; his three children: Anne, Sarah and J. Gregory Whitehead; two granddaughters; seven stepchildren; and 18 step-grandchildren.<ref name=\"nytimesobit\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.gs.com/our_firm/our_culture/social_responsibility/gs_foundation/articles/board_of_trustees_article_030616194436.html Goldman Sachs biography], gs.com; accessed February 14, 2015.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061006025538/http://www.clarke.edu/news/NDWMedallion/whitehead.htm Biodata], clarke.edu; accessed February 14, 2015.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20190126222118/http://www.amdec.org/ AMDeC Foundation]\n*{{C-SPAN|John Whitehead}}\n*[http://id.lib.harvard.edu/ead/bak00292/catalog John C. Whitehead papers] at Baker Library Special Collections, Harvard Business School.\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box | title=[[United States Deputy Secretary of State]]| before=[[Kenneth W. Dam]]| after=[[Lawrence Eagleburger]]| years=1985\u20131989}}\n{{s-bus}}\n{{succession box| title=[[Chair (official)|Chairman]] and [[CEO]], [[Goldman Sachs]]| before=[[Gus Levy]]|| after=[[John Weinberg]]| years=1976\u20131985}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{USDeputySecretaryofState}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Whitehead, John C.}}\n[[Category:1922 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:American investment bankers]]\n[[Category:American military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from New York City]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Chairmen of Goldman Sachs]]\n[[Category:Chief Executive Officers of Goldman Sachs]]\n[[Category:Distinguished Eagle Scouts]]\n[[Category:Harvard Business School alumni]]\n[[Category:Haverford College alumni]]\n[[Category:Members of the Steering Committee of the Bilderberg Group]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Republicans]]\n[[Category:Seton Hall University]]\n[[Category:People from Essex Fells, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from Evanston, Illinois]]\n[[Category:People from Montclair, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Place of death missing]]\n[[Category:Presidential Citizens Medal recipients]]\n[[Category:United States Deputy Secretaries of State]]\n[[Category:American Episcopalians]]\n[[Category:Writers from Evanston, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Writers from New Jersey]]\n", "name_user": "Akankshakhurana13", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added Safe Water Network as an organization co-founded by him and hyper linked Paul Newman and Safe Water Network", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_C._Whitehead"}
{"title_page": "Helensburgh Glow Worm Tunnel", "text_new": "{{Hatnote|For the current Helensburgh station, see [[Helensburgh railway station]]}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Orphan|date=June 2019}}\n{{underlinked|date=June 2019}}\n}}\nThe '''Helensburgh Glow Worm tunnel''' is a disused rail tunnel in [[Helensburgh, New South Wales]] that has become a popular tourist attraction due to its heritage status,<ref name=\"auto\"/> haunted history<ref name=\"auto1\"/> and most notably, its [[glow worm]] population.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>[[File:Helensburgh Tunnel (227543415).jpeg|thumb|Helensburgh Tunnel (227543415)]] It is owned by Crown Lands and taken care of by a community group Helensburgh Landcare, who in early 2019 restricted access to the tunnel for the conservation of the glow worm colony.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite news |last=Pearson |first=Andrew |date=3 July 2018 |title=Authorities confirm why Helensburgh glow worm tunnel was fenced off |url=https://www.illawarramercury.com.au/story/5500746/authorities-confirm-why-helensburgh-glow-worm-tunnel-was-fenced-off/ |newspaper=[[Illawarra Mercury]]|access-date=13 May 2019 }}</ref> Due to excessive flooding and to help the glow worm population recover, as of February 9 2020, the tunnel has been closed for an indefinite period.\n\n==History==\nThe Helensburgh Glow Worm tunnel was opened on January 1, 1889 and formed part of the town's [[Helensburgh railway station|first railway station]]. The original station was made up of two single line tunnels; a short \u2018Helensburgh tunnel\u2019 that ran 80 metres in length; and the \u2018Metropolitan tunnel\u2019 which was 624 metres long.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |url=https://www.environment.nsw.gov.au/heritageapp/ViewHeritageItemDetails.aspx?ID=4801137 |title=Helensburgh Railway Station Group |website=NSW office of Environment & Heritage |access-date=10 May 2019}}</ref> The latter is what is now locally known as the \u2018Helensburgh Glow Worm tunnel\u2019. The Metropolitan tunnel connected the local colliery to Helensburgh station as a way to transport mining produce uphill where it could be transported to suburbs to the north of Helensburgh.<ref name=\"auto4\">{{cite web |url=https://www.helensburgh.com.au/metropolitan-tunnel/ |title=Metropolitan Tunnel 1st (Tunnel No. 4) |last1=House |first1=Merylin |last2=Piggott |first2=Ian |website=Helensburgh |access-date=10 May 2019}}</ref>[[File:Old Helensburgh railway station, circa 1890\u20131905.png|thumb|Old Helensburgh railway station, circa 1890\u20131905]]\n\nThe tunnels and station were closed in 1915 when the train line was duplicated and moved to combine and simplify the Sutherland to Wollongong journey; a necessity due to the increased coal mining operations from Helensburgh and down the South Coast.<ref name=\"auto5\">{{cite web |url=https://historichelensburgh.org.au/articles-about-helensburgh-australia/helensburghs-railway-tunnels/ |title=Helensburgh's Railway Tunnels |website=Helensburgh and District Historical Society |access-date=13 May 2019}}</ref>  \nWith the two tunnels no longer in use, the colliery turned the Metropolitan tunnel into a reservoir for mining purposes. In May 1928 a concrete plug was installed at the southern end of the tunnel which allowed the mine to control the water that would flood the tunnel from the northern end.<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n\nIn April 1995, Metropolitan Colliery chose to clear years of debris and overgrowth at the northern entrance of the tunnel. After removing 2 metres of soil, several bricks from the original station platform were found. Helensburgh Landcare sought to excavate the site and was granted permission by the colliery to dig down to the original train track level.<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n\nIn 2001, Helensburgh Landcare was awarded a Centenary of Federation grant allowing them to transform the site into a historical attraction. To recreate a realistic tunnel, the ground was lay with ballast and then parts of the original train track taken from the colliery side of the tunnel were put down in place of the original line. Landcare also restored what was left of the original \u2018Helensburgh Station\u2019 sign, found in a gully close to the area.<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n\nOver the years, the site became frequented with locals, historians, tourists and photographers as well as colonies of [[glow worm]]s. \nIn 2012, the station sign was vandalised and removed, restored and reinstalled in 2015. Within 18 months the sign was vandalised again.<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n\nIn June 2018, a fence and gate were installed at the site in response to complaints made to the NSW department of Industry, to discourage vandalism and destruction of the site and glow worm colony.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n\nOn December 21, 2018 a new reserve was issued by the NSW government that marked the Metropolitan tunnel and Helensburgh tunnel had been set aside for \u201cpassive recreation, heritage purposes, environmental protection\u201d. Whilst Crown Lands retained ownership of the tunnels, this reserve appointed Helensburgh and District Landcare Group Inc as crown land manager, giving the group responsibility of the tunnels. Their first act as land management was to officially name the reserve, \u2018Helensburgh Station Reserve\u2019.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://gazette.legislation.nsw.gov.au/so/download.w3p?id=Gazette_2018_2018-144.pdf |title=Reservation of Crown Land |newspaper=[[Government Gazette of the state of NSW]] |volume=XL |issue=144 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=21 December 2018 |accessdate=17 May 2019 |page=33,[n2018\u20134353] |via=NSW Government}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2019, the group decided to closed the Metropolitan tunnel off from would-be visitors from January 7 to February 3, by locking the fence and blocking access to the tunnel for conservation purposes.\n\n==Local superstitions==\nThe Metropolitan and Helensburgh tunnel have become a popular attraction for those who believe in the paranormal. Some visitors report eerie feelings and supernatural encounters upon returning from either tunnel.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite news |last=Mardon |first=Cydonee |date=19 September 2016 |title=Like being spooked? Try the Helensburgh tunnels ghost tour experience |url=https://www.illawarramercury.com.au/story/4175363/like-being-spooked-try-the-helensburgh-tunnels-ghost-tour-experience/ |newspaper=[[Illawarra Mercury]]|access-date=12 May 2019 }}</ref> This is purported by a death that occurred in one of the tunnels on June 13, 1895.\n\nA miner named Robert Hails died in a train tunnel after he was run over and split in two by a train whilst trying to pass through the tunnel on foot. Which tunnel this accident occurred in is unknown, as multiple news sources were inconsistent when reporting the location of his demise.\n\nA local paper, the Illawarra Mercury wrote of the trial surrounding the death in its June 15, 1895 article;\n\n\u201cThe jury returned the following verdict \u2013 \u2018That deceased came to his death by injuries accidentally received on the 13th of May through being run over by a passing train \u2013 No.67 \u2013 in No. 2 tunnel on the Illawarra line.\u201d<ref name=\"auto6\">{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article132301619 |title=A FATAL ACCIDENT. |newspaper=[[Illawarra Mercury]] |volume=XL |issue=109 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=15 June 1895 |accessdate=17 May 2019 |page=2 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nAt the time, the extended Helensburgh rail area had 8 tunnels in total. The No. 2 tunnel was also known as the Cawley tunnel and is located to the north of the old Helensburgh station.\n\n\u201cHe had stayed rather late in the township and on going home had to pass through the tunnel where the accident occurred.\u201d <ref name=\"auto6\"/>\n\nThe Cawley township was in the opposite direction of Hailes\u2019 home in the suburb of Clifton. At the time, Cawley railway station was being used to receive goods for work on the railway, and to deliver supplies to the colliery. The township of Cawley had begun to disappear in 1888 when the Cawley post office had closed down.<ref name=\"auto5\"/>  The reason for its closure was a lack of business; 7 years had passed since work had finished on that section of the line and workers had moved further down to work on the Otford and Clifton sections of the line. Although it is possible he was visiting a friend who remained in the township, there is speculation that Robert having died in the Cawley tunnel is incorrect.<ref name=\"auto7\">{{cite web |url=https://www.helensburgh.com.au/death-in-the-railway-tunnel/ |title=Death in the Railway Tunnel |last=Piggott |first=Ian |website=Helensburgh |access-date=13 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nThere is reason to suggest that he may have travelled through either of the two Lilyvale tunnels, or the Metropolitan or Helensburgh tunnel. West Helensburgh had started to become a developed town and could have been a reason for him to go through the Metropolitan and Helensburgh tunnels. It is also argued that like many residents at the time, he may have used either of the two lilyvale tunnels which lead to the neighbouring suburb of Bulgo. An article from the Australian Star, published on June 14, 1895 gives an alternate view of events to its Illawarra Mercury counterpart.\n\n\u201cA wire from Wollongong says: \u2014 News is just to hand of a train fatality which occurred in the first tunnel this side of Helensburgh this morning\u2026\u201d<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article227115580 |title=RAILWAY FATALITY. |newspaper=[[The Australian Star]] |issue=2295 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=14 June 1895 |accessdate=17 May 2019 |page=6 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nAs this news came from Wollongong, then \u201cthis side of Helensburgh\u201d would refer only to tunnels south of Helensburgh; which would discount the Cawley tunnel. Interpretations of this may mean any of the 4 tunnels aforementioned.\n\nAnother article by the South Australian Chronicle, published on June 15, 1895 stated\n\n\u201cHe had apparently gone to sleep on the line in a short tunnel as he was returning home late last night from work.\u201d<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article93979481 |title=INTERCOLONIAL NEWS. |newspaper=[[South Australian Chronicle]] |volume=XXXVII |issue=1,921 |location=South Australia |date=15 June 1895 |accessdate=17 May 2019 |page=21 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nLocal historians believe \u2018short tunnel\u2019 would imply that he either met his death in the Lilyvale tunnel or the Helensburgh tunnel, which are both 80 metres in length.<ref name=\"auto7\"/> However, \u2018short\u2019 is relative and it remains a mystery as to the true location of Hailes deathplace.\n\nAnd yet out of these conflicting reports, a local legend that one can hear the footsteps of Robert Hailes trying to outrun the trains was conceived. The main Metropolitan tunnel and its companion the Helensburgh tunnel have since become a great source for ghost-tour operators in the south coast.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n==Glow worms==\nAfter the Metropolitan tunnel was restored, a colony of glow worms began to inhabit the inner part of the 24 metres stretch of excavated tunnel. These glow worms, also known as [[Fungus gnat|Fungus Gnats]] are famous for their bioluminescence.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.australiangeographic.com.au/topics/science-environment/2016/06/lighting-the-night-glow-worms-around-australia/ |title=Lighting the night: glow worms around Australia |website=Australian Geographic |access-date=10 May 2019}}</ref> It is the blue-green light that the worms emit, that attracts many visitors to the tunnel. It is also this light that lures the glow worm's prey \u2013 small invertebrate, for example mosquitoes.\n\nIn June 2018 a fence was constructed at the base of the entrance to the old station after\n\n\u201cThe [NSW department of Industry] received reports of damage to heritage items on the platform, and there are concerns about the impact of light, noise and pollution on the glow worms in the tunnel,\u201d.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n\nThe glow worm populations have been reduced<ref name=\"auto3\"/> in recent years by spectators to the tunnel interrupting the worms feeding processes by visitors\u2019 beaming flash lights onto the roof of the tunnel, sending up flares and firecrackers for photography purposes, and graffitiing the inner tunnel wall.\n\nToday, access to the tunnels is at the discretion of the Helensburgh Landcare group.<ref name=\"auto4\"/> The group blocked entrance to the tunnel for 4 weeks in January 2019<ref name=\"auto4\"/> during breeding season in an effort to allow the glow worm population to recover from years of poor treatment.\n\nWhen the gate is locked, visitors are prohibited by law from entering the tunnel. The tunnel now comes under the NSW Inclosed Lands Protection Act 1901, which makes trespassers liable to prosecution.\n\nAs of publishing, the tunnel is closed due to flooding and to let the glow worm population recover.\n\n==External links==\n{{Navbox\n | name  = Navbox/doc\n | title = [[Helensburgh, New South Wales|Helensburgh]]\n | listclass = hlist\n\n | group1 = Location\n | list1  =\n * [[Helensburgh, New South Wales]]\n\n | group2 = Wikivoyage\n | list2  =\n * [https://en.wikivoyage.org/wiki/Helensburgh_(New_South_Wales) Helensburgh (New South Wales)]\n\n | group3 = Major landmarks\n | list3  =\n * [[Symbio Wildlife Park]]\n\n[[Bald Hill (Australia)]]\n\n[[Helensburgh railway station]]\n\nHelensburgh Glow Worm Tunnel\n\n[https://www.svtsydney.org Sri Venkateswara Temple]\n }}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{coord missing|New South Wales}}\n\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Railway tunnels in New South Wales]]\n", "text_old": "{{Hatnote|For the current Helensburgh station, see [[Helensburgh railway station]]}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Orphan|date=June 2019}}\n{{underlinked|date=June 2019}}\n}}\nThe '''Helensburgh Glow Worm tunnel''' is a disused train tunnel in [[Helensburgh, New South Wales]] that has become a popular tourist attraction due to its heritage status,<ref name=\"auto\"/> haunted history<ref name=\"auto1\"/> and most notably, its [[glow worm]] population.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>[[File:Helensburgh Tunnel (227543415).jpeg|thumb|Helensburgh Tunnel (227543415)]] It is owned by Crown Lands and taken care of by a community group called Helensburgh Landcare, who in early 2019 restricted access to the tunnel for the conservation of the glow worm colony.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite news |last=Pearson |first=Andrew |date=3 July 2018 |title=Authorities confirm why Helensburgh glow worm tunnel was fenced off |url=https://www.illawarramercury.com.au/story/5500746/authorities-confirm-why-helensburgh-glow-worm-tunnel-was-fenced-off/ |newspaper=[[Illawarra Mercury]]|access-date=13 May 2019 }}</ref> Because of flooding and to help the glow worm population recover, as of February 9 2020, the tunnel has been CLOSED for an indefinite period.\n\n==History==\nThe Helensburgh Glow Worm tunnel was opened on January 1, 1889 and formed part of the town's [[Helensburgh railway station|first railway station]]. The original station was made up of two single line tunnels; a short \u2018Helensburgh tunnel\u2019 that ran 80 metres in length; and the \u2018Metropolitan tunnel\u2019 which was 624 metres long.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |url=https://www.environment.nsw.gov.au/heritageapp/ViewHeritageItemDetails.aspx?ID=4801137 |title=Helensburgh Railway Station Group |website=NSW office of Environment & Heritage |access-date=10 May 2019}}</ref> The latter is what is now locally known as the \u2018Helensburgh Glow Worm tunnel\u2019. The Metropolitan tunnel connected the local colliery to Helensburgh station as a way to transport mining produce uphill where it could be transported to suburbs to the north of Helensburgh.<ref name=\"auto4\">{{cite web |url=https://www.helensburgh.com.au/metropolitan-tunnel/ |title=Metropolitan Tunnel 1st (Tunnel No. 4) |last1=House |first1=Merylin |last2=Piggott |first2=Ian |website=Helensburgh |access-date=10 May 2019}}</ref>[[File:Old Helensburgh railway station, circa 1890\u20131905.png|thumb|Old Helensburgh railway station, circa 1890\u20131905]]\n\nThe tunnels and station were closed in 1915 when the train line was duplicated and moved to combine and simplify the Sutherland to Wollongong journey; a necessity due to the increased coal mining operations from Helensburgh and down the South Coast.<ref name=\"auto5\">{{cite web |url=https://historichelensburgh.org.au/articles-about-helensburgh-australia/helensburghs-railway-tunnels/ |title=Helensburgh's Railway Tunnels |website=Helensburgh and District Historical Society |access-date=13 May 2019}}</ref>  \nWith the two tunnels no longer in use, the colliery turned the Metropolitan tunnel into a reservoir for mining purposes. In May 1928 a concrete plug was installed at the southern end of the tunnel which allowed the mine to control the water that would flood the tunnel from the northern end.<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n\nIn April 1995, Metropolitan Colliery chose to clear years of debris and overgrowth at the northern entrance of the tunnel. After removing 2 metres of soil, several bricks from the original station platform were found. Helensburgh Landcare sought to excavate the site and was granted permission by the colliery to dig down to the original train track level.<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n\nIn 2001, Helensburgh Landcare was awarded a Centenary of Federation grant allowing them to transform the site into a historical attraction. To recreate a realistic tunnel, the ground was lay with ballast and then parts of the original train track taken from the colliery side of the tunnel were put down in place of the original line. Landcare also restored what was left of the original \u2018Helensburgh Station\u2019 sign, found in a gully close to the area.<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n\nOver the years, the site became frequented with locals, historians, tourists and photographers as well as colonies of [[glow worm]]s. \nIn 2012, the station sign was vandalised and removed, restored and reinstalled in 2015. Within 18 months the sign was vandalised again.<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n\nIn June 2018, a fence and gate were installed at the site in response to complaints made to the NSW department of Industry, to discourage vandalism and destruction of the site and glow worm colony.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n\nOn December 21, 2018 a new reserve was issued by the NSW government that marked the Metropolitan tunnel and Helensburgh tunnel had been set aside for \u201cpassive recreation, heritage purposes, environmental protection\u201d. Whilst Crown Lands retained ownership of the tunnels, this reserve appointed Helensburgh and District Landcare Group Inc as crown land manager, giving the group responsibility of the tunnels. Their first act as land management was to officially name the reserve, \u2018Helensburgh Station Reserve\u2019.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://gazette.legislation.nsw.gov.au/so/download.w3p?id=Gazette_2018_2018-144.pdf |title=Reservation of Crown Land |newspaper=[[Government Gazette of the state of NSW]] |volume=XL |issue=144 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=21 December 2018 |accessdate=17 May 2019 |page=33,[n2018\u20134353] |via=NSW Government}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2019, the group decided to closed the Metropolitan tunnel off from would-be visitors from January 7 to February 3, by locking the fence and blocking access to the tunnel for conservation purposes.\n\n==Local superstitions==\nThe Metropolitan and Helensburgh tunnel have become a popular attraction for those who believe in the paranormal. Some visitors report eerie feelings and supernatural encounters upon returning from either tunnel.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite news |last=Mardon |first=Cydonee |date=19 September 2016 |title=Like being spooked? Try the Helensburgh tunnels ghost tour experience |url=https://www.illawarramercury.com.au/story/4175363/like-being-spooked-try-the-helensburgh-tunnels-ghost-tour-experience/ |newspaper=[[Illawarra Mercury]]|access-date=12 May 2019 }}</ref> This is purported by a death that occurred in one of the tunnels on June 13, 1895.\n\nA miner named Robert Hails died in a train tunnel after he was run over and split in two by a train whilst trying to pass through the tunnel on foot. Which tunnel this accident occurred in is unknown, as multiple news sources were inconsistent when reporting the location of his demise.\n\nA local paper, the Illawarra Mercury wrote of the trial surrounding the death in its June 15, 1895 article;\n\n\u201cThe jury returned the following verdict \u2013 \u2018That deceased came to his death by injuries accidentally received on the 13th of May through being run over by a passing train \u2013 No.67 \u2013 in No. 2 tunnel on the Illawarra line.\u201d<ref name=\"auto6\">{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article132301619 |title=A FATAL ACCIDENT. |newspaper=[[Illawarra Mercury]] |volume=XL |issue=109 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=15 June 1895 |accessdate=17 May 2019 |page=2 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nAt the time, the extended Helensburgh rail area had 8 tunnels in total. The No. 2 tunnel was also known as the Cawley tunnel and is located to the north of the old Helensburgh station.\n\n\u201cHe had stayed rather late in the township and on going home had to pass through the tunnel where the accident occurred.\u201d <ref name=\"auto6\"/>\n\nThe Cawley township was in the opposite direction of Hailes\u2019 home in the suburb of Clifton. At the time, Cawley railway station was being used to receive goods for work on the railway, and to deliver supplies to the colliery. The township of Cawley had begun to disappear in 1888 when the Cawley post office had closed down.<ref name=\"auto5\"/>  The reason for its closure was a lack of business; 7 years had passed since work had finished on that section of the line and workers had moved further down to work on the Otford and Clifton sections of the line. Although it is possible he was visiting a friend who remained in the township, there is speculation that Robert having died in the Cawley tunnel is incorrect.<ref name=\"auto7\">{{cite web |url=https://www.helensburgh.com.au/death-in-the-railway-tunnel/ |title=Death in the Railway Tunnel |last=Piggott |first=Ian |website=Helensburgh |access-date=13 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nThere is reason to suggest that he may have travelled through either of the two Lilyvale tunnels, or the Metropolitan or Helensburgh tunnel. West Helensburgh had started to become a developed town and could have been a reason for him to go through the Metropolitan and Helensburgh tunnels. It is also argued that like many residents at the time, he may have used either of the two lilyvale tunnels which lead to the neighbouring suburb of Bulgo. An article from the Australian Star, published on June 14, 1895 gives an alternate view of events to its Illawarra Mercury counterpart.\n\n\u201cA wire from Wollongong says: \u2014 News is just to hand of a train fatality which occurred in the first tunnel this side of Helensburgh this morning\u2026\u201d<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article227115580 |title=RAILWAY FATALITY. |newspaper=[[The Australian Star]] |issue=2295 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=14 June 1895 |accessdate=17 May 2019 |page=6 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nAs this news came from Wollongong, then \u201cthis side of Helensburgh\u201d would refer only to tunnels south of Helensburgh; which would discount the Cawley tunnel. Interpretations of this may mean any of the 4 tunnels aforementioned.\n\nAnother article by the South Australian Chronicle, published on June 15, 1895 stated\n\n\u201cHe had apparently gone to sleep on the line in a short tunnel as he was returning home late last night from work.\u201d<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article93979481 |title=INTERCOLONIAL NEWS. |newspaper=[[South Australian Chronicle]] |volume=XXXVII |issue=1,921 |location=South Australia |date=15 June 1895 |accessdate=17 May 2019 |page=21 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nLocal historians believe \u2018short tunnel\u2019 would imply that he either met his death in the Lilyvale tunnel or the Helensburgh tunnel, which are both 80 metres in length.<ref name=\"auto7\"/> However, \u2018short\u2019 is relative and it remains a mystery as to the true location of Hailes deathplace.\n\nAnd yet out of these conflicting reports, a local legend that one can hear the footsteps of Robert Hailes trying to outrun the trains was conceived. The main Metropolitan tunnel and its companion the Helensburgh tunnel have since become a great source for ghost-tour operators in the south coast.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n==Glow worms==\nAfter the Metropolitan tunnel was restored, a colony of glow worms began to inhabit the inner part of the 24 metres stretch of excavated tunnel. These glow worms, also known as [[Fungus gnat|Fungus Gnats]] are famous for their bioluminescence.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.australiangeographic.com.au/topics/science-environment/2016/06/lighting-the-night-glow-worms-around-australia/ |title=Lighting the night: glow worms around Australia |website=Australian Geographic |access-date=10 May 2019}}</ref> It is the blue-green light that the worms emit, that attracts many visitors to the tunnel. It is also this light that lures the glow worm's prey \u2013 small invertebrate, for example mosquitoes.\n\nIn June 2018 a fence was constructed at the base of the entrance to the old station after\n\n\u201cThe [NSW department of Industry] received reports of damage to heritage items on the platform, and there are concerns about the impact of light, noise and pollution on the glow worms in the tunnel,\u201d.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n\nThe glow worm populations have been reduced<ref name=\"auto3\"/> in recent years by spectators to the tunnel interrupting the worms feeding processes by visitors\u2019 beaming flash lights onto the roof of the tunnel, sending up flares and firecrackers for photography purposes, and graffitiing the inner tunnel wall.\n\nToday, access to the tunnels is at the discretion of the Helensburgh Landcare group.<ref name=\"auto4\"/> The group blocked entrance to the tunnel for 4 weeks in January 2019<ref name=\"auto4\"/> during breeding season in an effort to allow the glow worm population to recover from years of poor treatment.\n\nWhen the gate is locked, visitors are prohibited by law from entering the tunnel. The tunnel now comes under the NSW Inclosed Lands Protection Act 1901, which makes trespassers liable to prosecution.\n\nAs of publishing, the tunnel is closed due to flooding and to let the glow worm population recover.\n\n==External links==\n{{Navbox\n | name  = Navbox/doc\n | title = [[Helensburgh, New South Wales|Helensburgh]]\n | listclass = hlist\n\n | group1 = Location\n | list1  =\n * [[Helensburgh, New South Wales]]\n\n | group2 = Wikivoyage\n | list2  =\n * [https://en.wikivoyage.org/wiki/Helensburgh_(New_South_Wales) Helensburgh (New South Wales)]\n\n | group3 = Major landmarks\n | list3  =\n * [[Symbio Wildlife Park]]\n\n[[Bald Hill (Australia)]]\n\n[[Helensburgh railway station]]\n\nHelensburgh Glow Worm Tunnel\n\n[https://www.svtsydney.org Sri Venkateswara Temple]\n }}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{coord missing|New South Wales}}\n\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Railway tunnels in New South Wales]]\n", "name_user": "Astdb", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Helensburgh_Glow_Worm_Tunnel"}
{"title_page": "Trejsi Sejdini", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{short description|Miss Universe Albania 2018}}\n{{Infobox pageant titleholder\n| image        =\n| birth_name   = \n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|2000|5|30}}<ref name=page>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pageantplanet.com/profiles/trejsi-sejdini|archiveurl=http://archive.today/20190331003006/https://www.pageantplanet.com/profiles/trejsi-sejdini|url-status=dead|title=Trejsi Sejdini|website=Pageantplanet.com|archive-date=23 July 2019}}</ref><ref name=sorry>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailyxing.com/lajm/14854/i-cmendi-djemte-me-fotot-provokuese-por-nuk-do-ta-besoni-sa-vjec-eshte-trejsi-sejdini/eng/|archiveurl=http://archive.today/20190330235612/https://www.dailyxing.com/lajm/14854/i-cmendi-djemte-me-fotot-provokuese-por-nuk-do-ta-besoni-sa-vjec-eshte-trejsi-sejdini/eng/|url-status=dead|title=I&#39;m sorry guys with provocative photos, but you will not believe how old is Trejd Sejdini|website=Dailyxing.com|archive-date=23 July 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_place  = [[Elbasan]],<ref name=page/><ref name=lives>{{Cite web|url=https://www.missuniverse.com/contestant/1000529|archiveurl=http://archive.today/20190331004255/https://www.missuniverse.com/contestant/1000529|url-status=dead|title=Miss Universe Home|website=Missuniverse.com|archive-date=23 July 2019}}</ref> [[Albania]] {{flagicon|ALB}}\n| title        = [[Miss Universe Albania|Miss Universe Albania 2018]]\n| competitions = [[Miss Universe Albania|Miss Universe Albania 2018]]<br>(Winner)<br>[[Miss Universe 2018]]<br>(Unplaced)\n| height       = {{height|m=1.83}}<ref name=lives/>\n| eye_color    = [[Eye color#Green|Green]]\n| hair_color   = [[Blond]]e\n}}\n\n'''Trejsi Sejdini''' (born May 30, 2000) is an Albanian model,social media personality, sex symbol, television personality and beauty pageant titleholder who was crowned [[Miss Universe Albania]] 2018<ref name=klip>{{Cite web|url=http://story.al/trejsi-sejdini-ne-miss-universe-klip-nga-jeta-ime-e-perditshme-shihni-se-si-une/|archiveurl=http://archive.today/20190620101114/http://story.al/trejsi-sejdini-ne-miss-universe-klip-nga-jeta-ime-e-perditshme-shihni-se-si-une/|url-status=dead|title=Trejsi Sejdini: N\u00eb \u201cMiss Universe\u201d me klip nga jeta ime e p\u00ebrditshme, do shihni se si un\u00eb \u2026|date=November 15, 2018|website=Story.al|archive-date=23 July 2019}}</ref> and represented [[Albania]] at the [[Miss Universe 2018]].<ref name=klip/><ref name=page/><ref name=sorry/><ref name=klip/><ref name=page/><ref name=sorry/> \n\n==Personal life==\nSejdini was born in [[Elbasan]], [[Albania]] in 2000. In addition to her native language (Albanian), she speaks 3 foreign languages, namely Italian, French and English.<ref name=lives/> <ref name=lives/> She lives in [[Tirana]].<ref name=lives/> Sejdini joined various clips<ref>[http://archive.is/pFhiq] {{dead link|date=July 2019}}</ref> as a model (the most famous are ''Gang gang'' by Fero<ref>{{Cite web|title=Fero - Gang Gang|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=w7IThtyR220|website=Youtube.com|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref> and ''Jealousy'' by Mozzik)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rdwViLd4yK8|title=YouTube|website=Youtube.com}}</ref> in [[Albania]]. Sejdini participated, at the age of 16,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.revistavip.club/njihuni-trejsi-sejdini-konkurrente-e-miss-universe-albania-2016/|archiveurl=http://archive.today/20190331011638/http://www.revistavip.club/njihuni-trejsi-sejdini-konkurrente-e-miss-universe-albania-2016/|url-status=dead|title=Njihuni me Trejsi Sejdini, konkurrente e Miss Universe Albania 2016|archive-date=23 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.missosology.info/forum/viewtopic.php|archiveurl=http://archive.today/20190331010455/http://www.missosology.info/forum/viewtopic.php?f=3&t=963918|url-status=dead|title=Could Trejsi Sejdini win MISS UNIVERSE ?|archive-date=23 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://albanianbeauty.wordpress.com/2016/05/16/miss-albania-universe-2016-contestants/|archiveurl=http://archive.today/20190331010220/https://albanianbeauty.wordpress.com/2016/05/16/miss-albania-universe-2016-contestants/|url-status=dead|title=MISS ALBANIA UNIVERSE 2016 Contestants|date=May 16, 2016|archive-date=23 July 2019}}</ref> in ''[[Miss Universe Albania]] 2016'' pageant,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/pages/category/Public-Figure/trejsisejdinimiss/about/|archiveurl=http://archive.today/20190331005827/https://www.facebook.com/pg/trejsisejdinimiss/about/?ref=page_internal|url-status=dead|title=Trejsi Sejdini - Miss Universe Albania 2016|website=Facebook.com|archive-date=23 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pageantsnews.com/en/news/international-contests/miss-universe/4092-miss-albania-universe-2016-meet-the-candidates|archiveurl=http://archive.today/20190331011604/https://pageantsnews.com/en/news/international-contests/miss-universe/4092-miss-albania-universe-2016-meet-the-candidates|url-status=dead|title=Miss Albania Universe 2016 : Meet the candidates|archive-date=23 July 2019}}</ref> but she did not win even though she was one of the favorite competitors.<ref>[http://archive.today/585BK]</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thegreatpageantcommunity.com/2016/04/18/miss-universe-albania-2016-meet-contestants/|archiveurl=http://archive.today/20190331011537/https://thegreatpageantcommunity.com/2016/04/18/miss-universe-albania-2016-meet-contestants/|url-status=dead|title=Miss Universe Albania 2016 [Meet the Contestants]|date=April 17, 2016|website=Thegreatpageantcommunity.com|archive-date=23 July 2019}}</ref> She won<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oranews.tv/article/shpallet-miss-universe-albania-ja-kush-do-na-perfaqesoje-ne-amerike|archiveurl=http://archive.today/20190331013442/http://www.oranews.tv/article/shpallet-miss-universe-albania-ja-kush-do-na-perfaqesoje-ne-amerike|url-status=dead|title=Shpallet Miss Universe Albania, ja kush do na p\u00ebrfaq\u00ebsoj\u00eb n\u00eb Amerik\u00eb|website=Oranews.tv|archive-date=23 July 2019}}</ref> the ''[[Miss Universe Albania]] 2018'' pageant in June 2018 at ''Pallati i Kongreseve''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://awardgoesto.com/miss-universe-albania-2018-trejsi-sejdini/|archiveurl=http://archive.today/20190331003724/http://awardgoesto.com/miss-universe-albania-2018-trejsi-sejdini/|url-status=dead|title=Miss Universe Albania 2018 award goes to Trejsi Sejdini|date=June 19, 2018|website=Awardgoesto.com|archive-date=23 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rankmylist.com/list/who-will-win-miss-universe-2018/trejsi-sejdini-albania/9aa6034ece0|archiveurl=http://archive.today/20190331010714/https://www.rankmylist.com/list/who-will-win-miss-universe-2018/trejsi-sejdini-albania/9aa6034ece0|url-status=dead|title=Trejsi Sejdini (Albania) [Who will win Miss Universe 2018?]|website=Rankmylist.com|archive-date=23 July 2019}}</ref> She represented, at the age of 18,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/MemesQueenOficial/posts/1739855596098500|archiveurl=http://archive.today/20190331013428/https://www.facebook.com/MemesQueenOficial/posts/trejsi-sejdini-miss-albania-universo-2018-tiene-18-a%C3%B1os-y-183m-de-estatura-insol/1739855596098500/%23|url-status=dead|title=MEMES QUEEN|website=Facebook.com|archive-date=23 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.khaosodenglish.com/culture/net/2018/12/14/why-thai-fans-are-all-about-miss-universe-albania/|title=Why Thai Fans Are All About Miss Universe Albania|first1=Asaree|last1=Thaitrakulpanich|first2=Staff|last2=Reporter|date=December 14, 2018}}</ref> her country ([[Albania]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.globalbeauties.com/news/2018/6/7/miss-universe-albania-2018-crowned|archiveurl=http://archive.today/20190331012539/https://www.globalbeauties.com/news/2018/6/7/miss-universe-albania-2018-crowned|url-status=dead|title=Miss Universe Albania 2018 Crowned|website=Globalbeauties.com|archive-date=23 July 2019}}</ref> at the ''[[Miss Universe 2018]]'' pageant in December 2018.<ref name=lives/> \n\n==Pageantry==\n===Miss Universe Albania 2018===\nSejdini was crowned<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newsbomb.al/trejsi-sejdini-shpallet-fituese-e-miss-universe-albania-fotot-123521|archiveurl=http://archive.today/20190331014048/https://www.newsbomb.al/trejsi-sejdini-shpallet-fituese-e-miss-universe-albania-fotot-123521|url-status=dead|title=Trejsi Sejdini shpallet fituese e 'Miss Universe Albania' (FOTOT)|website=Newsbomb.al|archive-date=23 July 2019}}</ref> as ''[[Miss Universe Albania]] 2018'' pageant<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://telegrafi.com/trejsi-sejdini-shpallet-miss-universe-albania/|archiveurl=http://archive.today/20190620092153/https://telegrafi.com/trejsi-sejdini-shpallet-miss-universe-albania/|url-status=dead|title=Trejsi Sejdini shpallet Miss Universe Albania|date=June 7, 2018|website=Telegrafi.com|archive-date=23 July 2019}}</ref> on June 6, 2018 and she also was awarded ''Miss Social Media''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://missosology.org/miss-universe/49770-miss-universe-albania-2018-is-trejsi-sejdini/|archiveurl=http://archive.today/20190331013224/http://missosology.org/miss-universe/49770-miss-universe-albania-2018-is-trejsi-sejdini/|url-status=dead|title=Miss Universe Albania 2018 is Trejsi Sejdini|date=June 7, 2018|archive-date=23 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Miss Universe 2018===\nSejdini represented [[Albania]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.universalqueen.com/2018/06/trejsi-sejdini-wins-miss-universe.html|archiveurl=http://archive.today/20190331014541/http://www.universalqueen.com/2018/06/trejsi-sejdini-wins-miss-universe.html|url-status=dead|title=Trejsi Sejdini wins Miss Universe Albania 2018|archive-date=23 July 2019}}</ref> at ''[[Miss Universe 2018]]'' pageant<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://businessmirror.com.ph/2018/12/17/best-of-2018-miss-universe-most-likely/|archiveurl=http://archive.today/20190331014702/https://businessmirror.com.ph/2018/12/17/best-of-2018-miss-universe-most-likely/|url-status=dead|title=Best of 2018: Miss Universe most likely|first=Miss|last=Charlize|archive-date=23 July 2019}}</ref> on December 17, 2018 and she was awarded ''Miss Photogenic''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://realityhouse.it/forum/la-piazza/catriona-gray-%F0%9F%87%B5%F0%9F%87%AD-e-miss-universo-2018/|archiveurl=http://archive.today/20190331014415/https://realityhouse.it/forum/la-piazza/catriona-gray-%F0%9F%87%B5%F0%9F%87%AD-e-miss-universo-2018/|url-status=dead|title=Catriona Gray \ud83c\uddf5\ud83c\udded \u00e8 Miss Universo 2018 &#124; La Piazza &#124; Home Page|website=Realityhouse.it|archive-date=23 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://plugtimes.com/2018/12/catriona-gray-wins-miss-universe-2018/|archiveurl=http://archive.today/20190331015007/https://plugtimes.com/2018/12/catriona-gray-wins-miss-universe-2018/|url-status=dead|title=Catriona Gray wins Miss Universe 2018|date=December 17, 2018|archive-date=23 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name}} \n*[http://www.revistavip.club/ revistavip.club/miss universe albania]\n*[http://missuniverse.com/ missuniverse.com]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-ach}}\n{{S-bef|before=Blerta Leka}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Miss Universe Albania]]| years = 2018}}\n{{S-aft|after= [[Cindy Marina]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Miss Universe 2018 delegates}}\n{{Authority control}}{{Albania-bio-stub}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sejdini, Trejsi}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:2000 births]]\n[[Category:Albanian female models]]\n[[Category:Miss Universe 2018 contestants]]\n[[Category:Albanian beauty pageant winners]]\n[[Category:People from Elbasan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{short description|Miss Universe Albania 2018}}\n{{Infobox pageant titleholder\n| image        =\n| birth_name   = \n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|2000|5|30}}<ref name=page>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pageantplanet.com/profiles/trejsi-sejdini|archiveurl=http://archive.today/20190331003006/https://www.pageantplanet.com/profiles/trejsi-